sentences: Marshall Garnett Grant (May 5, 1928 – August 7, 2011) was the upright bassist and electric bassist of singer Johnny Cash's original backing duo, the Tennessee Two, in which Grant and electric guitarist Luther Perkins played.
The group became known as The Tennessee Three in 1960, with the addition of drummer W. S. Holland.
He was one of twelve children born of Willie Leander (1888–1968) and Mary Elizabeth (Simmonds) Grant (1895–1965).

Grant married Etta May Dickerson on November 9, 1946.
Grant married Etta May Dickerson on November 9, 1946.
Grant and his wife settled in Memphis, Tennessee in 1947.
During the formation of this group, Cash used Grant's Martin guitar for performances, and for many years thereafter, for songwriting.
He recorded with Cash from 1954 until 1980.
He recorded with Cash from 1954 until 1980.
In the early 1970s, he briefly endorsed Micro-Frets instruments and Sunn amplifiers.
In 1980, Grant filed suit against Cash for wrongful dismissal and for embezzlement of retirement funds.
Grant made a final appearance onstage with Cash in 1999 as an original member of The Tennessee Two.
Following his career with Cash, Grant managed the Statler Brothers until their retirement in 2002.
Grant's autobiographical book I Was There When It Happened: My Life With Johnny Cash was published in October 2006.
He "laid down [his] bass for the last time" at the Brooks Museum in Memphis, Tennessee, in August 2010.
"Etta's Tune" included on Rosanne Cash's 2014 album, The River and the Thread, is dedicated to Grant and his wife.
For many years, Grant owned and raced outboard powerboats.
Marshall Grant is played by Larry Bagby in the 2005 film, Walk the Line
Marshall Grant died at the age of 83 on August 7, 2011 while in Jonesboro, Arkansas attending a festival to restore the childhood home of Johnny Cash.
